The question contains a logical trap rather than a legal one: if a man has a widow, he is dead. A widow is, by definition, the surviving wife of a deceased man. So a dead man cannot marry anyone, his late wife's sister included.

This is the same puzzle as the old riddle about whether a man may marry his widow's sister, the answer to which is simply "no, because he's dead."

But setting the riddle aside, you might be asking the substantive question: in the Falkland Islands, may a widow marry her late husband's brother, or may a widower marry his late wife's sister? That is a real historical question. Marriage to a deceased spouse's sibling was once prohibited in English law (the "prohibited degrees of affinity"), a rule that generated the famous Deceased Wife's Sister's Marriage Act 1907 and the Deceased Brother's Widow's Marriage Act 1921, which removed those bars in England.

The Falkland Islands are a British Overseas Territory with their own legislature, but their law derives heavily from English law. Marriage there is governed by the Marriage Ordinance. Affinity-based prohibitions of that 19th-century type have long since been abolished throughout the relevant legal tradition, so a surviving spouse marrying a deceased spouse's sibling would not run into that old impediment today.

If you want, I can look up the current text of the Falkland Islands Marriage Ordinance to confirm exactly what the prohibited degrees are now—but the literal answer to your question as phrased is that a dead man can't marry at all.
